    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-02-02T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-02-02T21:00:00-05:00" n="329"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d329">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7671: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-02-03T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 3, 1943—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>184. To Secretary of the Treasury from Adler. TF–89. In accordance with article 1
                        (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) of the Sino-American agreement of April 1, 1941,
                    Board asks me to consult you on the desirability of investing the United States
                    $2,000,000 in its account with the Federal Reserve Bank in direct obligations of
                    the Government of the United States. The Board is receiving sufficient United
                    States dollars from remittances to meet its out-payments for the next few months
                    with respect to both direct applications for foreign exchange and to its
                    obligations to the Central Bank under the November 1 agreement without having to
                    draw on the United States $2,000,000 in the Federal Reserve Bank. [Adler.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
